would you suggest handling books different to articles/... in the No DOI/ISBN case? Is crossref a reliable tool here or should we fall back to a different lookup?
Architected type-based dispatch routing books to catalogs, articles to Crossref

Yes — I'd split by type there, and no, Crossref isn't the right tool for books in that case.

The reason is what Crossref fundamentally is: a DOI registry built around journal articles and conference papers. Books are increasingly registered (Springer, Cambridge, Oxford, De Gruyter all do it), but coverage is uneven — older books, university-press titles that never registered DOIs, and anything from before DOIs were common simply aren't there. And there's a self-selection tell: if a book were in Crossref, it would have a DOI, which you'd usually already have in the entry. So a book with no DOI and no ISBN is close to the worst case for Crossref — it's exactly the population Crossref is least likely to know. Even when a book is in Crossref, its bibliographic/title search ranks books poorly next to articles and can hand back a single chapter or a different edition instead of the monograph you meant.

For books, the reliable fallback is a book-native catalog that indexes by title and author comprehensively. Two free, keyless options fit what the script already uses:

    Open Library search — https://openlibrary.org/search.json?title=...&author=..., which returns title, author_name, first_publish_year, publisher, and the ISBNs.
    Google Books — q=intitle:...+inauthor:..., returning the same volumeInfo shape the ISBN path already parses.

The useful part is that a title/author hit gives you the ISBN, so you can then route it straight into the ISBN handler you already have — and write that ISBN back with --out, which is the book analogue of recovering a DOI.

So the design I'd suggest: in the no-DOI branch, dispatch on entry type. Article-like types (@article, @inproceedings, …) keep the Crossref title search, which is genuinely good there. Book-like types (@book, @inbook, @incollection, @proceedings) go to Open Library, then Google Books, to recover the ISBN and metadata.

Two honest caveats that shape how to use the result rather than whether to. Catalog metadata is messier than publisher metadata — Open Library is partly crowd-sourced, and Google Books' scan-derived dates and merged editions are sometimes wrong — so they're excellent for finding a book but I'd treat the returned year/publisher as lower-confidence. And books have far more editions and reprints than articles, so a title match is easier to get subtly wrong. For both reasons I'd have the book path report the candidate with its ISBN for you to confirm rather than silently auto-accepting it the way the article path trusts a high title score, and I'd match on title+author while not failing on a year gap (the edition you cite may differ from first_publish_year).

